Key Applications
•	Biopharmaceutical Manufacturing: Biosensors are extensively used to monitor cell cultures during the production of therapeutic proteins, monoclonal antibodies, and vaccines.
•	Stem Cell Research: These devices ensure the maintenance of stem cells in ideal conditions, crucial for regenerative medicine and tissue engineering.
•	Academic and Clinical Research: Research institutions rely on biosensors for accurate and consistent data in cell culture experiments.
Market Challenges
•	High Initial Costs: The cost of advanced biosensors and integration with existing systems can be prohibitive, particularly for smaller research laboratories.
•	Complex Calibration and Maintenance: Ensuring accuracy over time requires regular calibration and maintenance, which can be resource-intensive.
•	Regulatory Hurdles: Strict regulatory requirements for devices used in biopharmaceutical production can slow down market entry and adoption.
